i## Registration Procedure		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iWhen I wrote my previous guide in 2017,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
1Joining DN42 Experimental Network (Chinese Only)	/article/modify-website/join-dn42-experimental-network.lantian	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i,ithe user information as well as ASN and IP are all managed from a		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isystem called Monotone. But in year 2018, DN42 gave up on Monotone and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iswitched to Git.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i**WARNING:** The registration procedure to DN42 is long and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icomplicated, since the procedure to register ASN and IP in real		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iInternet is similar, and DN42's goal is being a replication of real		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iInternet.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i**ATTENTION:**		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- The procedure here may become outdated as DN42 updates its		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  registration procedures. Please refer to DN42's official guides		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  first, and use my guide only as reference.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- [DN42 Registration Procedure on Official Wiki](https://dn42.dev/howto/Getting-Started)		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- [DN42 Git Guide (Creating Pull Request) on Official Wiki](https://git.dn42.dev/dn42/registry/src/branch/master/README.md)		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iIn addition, since a bunch of UNIX tools (such as Git, GnuPG) are		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
irequired in the procedure:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- It's recommended to use Linux or macOS for the whole procedure.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- If you use Windows, you may try		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  [Windows Subsystem for Linux](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/wsl/install-win10).		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iHere are the steps:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i1. First, go to <https://git.dn42.dev> and register an account. This		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   is the GitHub for DN42, and the account information is stored in		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   one of the git repos.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i2. Visit [dn42/registry](https://git.dn42.dev/dn42/registry), the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   account information repo, and `git clone` it to your local machine.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - Previously you need to fork the repo, but now DN42 has simplified		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     the process, and you only need to create a branch.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i3. Create a new branch named after		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   `[NICKNAME]-[Date, YYYYMMDD]/[Custom Branch Name]`.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - Assume I want to register on 2020-09-01, my branch name will be		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     `lantian-20200901/register`.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - Run these two lines to create your branch and upload it. Remember		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     to replace with your own branch name:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     ```bash		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     git checkout -b lantian-20200901/register		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     git push --set-upstream origin lantian-20200901/register		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     ```		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i4. Now you need to create a series of files in the cloned repo,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   including:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   1. Create a file `[NICKNAME]-MNT` under `data/mntner` directory,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      this file is your account that authorizes your further		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      operations. For example, this is my `mntner` file (available		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      under `data/mntner/LANTIAN-MNT`):		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      ```bash		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      mntner:             LANTIAN-MNT		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      admin-c:            LANTIAN-DN42		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      tech-c:             LANTIAN-DN42		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      mnt-by:             LANTIAN-MNT		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      source:             DN42		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      auth:               pgp-fingerprint 23067C13B6AEBDD7C0BB567327F31700E751EC22		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      auth:               ssh-rsa 		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      remarks:            pin-sha256:o1lfYvcdcYy81UIuZMZO1CkCLX+vJOdD5GLw1cmeStU=		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      ```		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      - The items in the file are:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        - `mntner`: `maintainer`, the name for your account. Same as		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i          file name.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        - `admin-c`: `admin contact`, point to a later created		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i          `person` file. Usually `[NICKNAME]-DN42`.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        - `tech-c`: `tech contact`, point to a later created `person`		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i          file. Usually `[NICKNAME]-DN42`.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        - `mnt-by`: `maintain by`, points to this account itself.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i          Usually `[NICKNAME]-DN42`.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        - `source`: has a fixed value of `DN42`.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        - `auth`: your authentication info. Usually two types of data		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i          are accepted: GPG public key and SSH public key.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i          - You **MUST** add at least one out of GPG pubkey and SSH		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i            pubkey.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i          - If you plan to add a GPG pubkey, you need to create one		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i            first (assuming you don't have one), for example following		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i            [this guide by GitHub](https://docs.github.com/en/free-pro-team@latest/github/authenticating-to-github/generating-a-new-gpg-key).		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i            You will also need the pubkey when submitting your		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i            registration request.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i            - You also need to upload your GPG pubkey to a public		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i              server, aka Keyserver, for other people to obtain.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i            - Run this command:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i              - `gpg --keyserver hkp://keyserver.ubuntu.com --send-key [GPG Key ID]`		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i            - Then fill the key ID to `auth` item, with format like		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i              `pgp-fingerprint [GPG Key ID]`, similar to my example		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i              above.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i          - If you plan to add a SSH pubkey, you need to create one		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i            first (assuming you don't have one).		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i            - Running `ssh-keygen -t ed25519` is usually enough for		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i              Mac and Linux, but if you have a rather old version of		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i              SSH which doesn't support ED25519 crypto, you may run		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i              `ssh-keygen -t rsa` instead to use RSA crypto.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i            - For Windows, you can		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i              [download PuTTY](https://www.chiark.greenend.org.uk/~sgtatham/putty/latest.html)		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i              and use its `puttygen` utility.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i            - After generation, add your pubkey (usually stored at		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i              `~/.ssh` and named `id_ed25519.pub` or `id_rsa.pub` on		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i              Mac and Linux; displayed straight on `puttygen` window		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i              after generation) to `auth` item, with format		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i              `ssh-ed25519 [SSH Pubkey]` or `ssh-rsa [SSH Pubkey]`.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i            - In addition, some services on DN42 verifies your		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i              identity with your SSH pubkey here.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i          - Read DN42's		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i            [Registry Authentication Wiki Page](https://dn42.dev/howto/Registry-Authentication)		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i            for more information.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        - `remarks`: comments, fill with whatever content you like. Or		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i          you may simply remove them.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      - **ATTENTION:** There is a long sequence of spaces between the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        name and values. The length of this space sequence **cannot be		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        changed to whatever you like, and cannot be replaced with		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        TAB**. the length of name, the colon, and the spaces **MUST be		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        exactly 20 characters**.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
